{"title_page": "Desperate Trails (1921 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1921 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Desperate Trails\n| image          = Desperate Trails (1921).jpg\n| caption        = Film still\n| director       = [[John Ford]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Elliott J. Clawson]]<br>[[Courtney Ryley Cooper]]\n| starring       = [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]]<br>[[Irene Rich]]<br>[[Barbara La Marr]] \n| cinematography = [[Robert De Grasse]]<br>Harry M. Fowler\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Film Manufacturing Company]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1921|6}}\n| runtime        = 50 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n\n'''''Desperate Trails''''' is a 1921 American [[Western (genre)|western]] film directed by [[John Ford]] and featuring [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]]. The film is considered to be [[lost film|lost]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DesperateTrails1921.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''Desperate Trails'' |accessdate=March 1, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAs described in a film publication,<ref name=\"FilmDaily\">{{cite journal |title=''Desperate Trails'': Carey Has a Good Story With His Most Recent Universal |journal=Film Daily |volume=16 |issue=86 |page=15 |publisher=Wyd's Films and Film Folks, Inc. |location=New York City |date=June 26, 1921 |url=https://archive.org/details/filmdailyvolume11516newy |accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> Bart Carson (Carey) is in love with Lou (La Marr) and even goes to jail to save Walter A. Walker (Coxen), a man she says is her brother but who is really a husband who has deserted his wife and two children. After he learns the truth, Bart breaks out of jail and trails Walter, who falls off a train trying to escape. Bart then seeks refuge in a cabin with Mrs. Walker (Rich),  where he is captured, but the officials have learned the truth and promise him a pardon.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]] as Bart Carson\n* [[Irene Rich]] as Mrs. Walker\n* George Stone as Dannie Boy\n* Helen Field as Carrie\n* [[Edward Coxen]] as Walter A. Walker\n* [[Barbara La Marr]] as Lady Lou\n* [[George Siegmann]] as Sheriff Price\n* Charles Inslee as Doc Higgins (as Charles E. Insley)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Harry Carey filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Desperate Trails}}\n* {{IMDb title|0012102}}\n\n{{John Ford |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Desperate Trails}}\n[[Category:1921 films]]\n[[Category:1920s Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Ford]]\n[[Category:Lost Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Lost American films]]\n[[Category:1921 lost films]]\n\n{{1920s-silent-Western-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1921 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Desperate Trails\n| image          = Desperate Trails (1921).jpg\n| caption        = Film still\n| director       = [[John Ford]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Elliott J. Clawson]]<br>[[Courtney Ryley Cooper]]\n| starring       = [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]]<br>[[Irene Rich]]<br>[[Barbara La Marr]] \n| cinematography = [[Robert De Grasse]]<br>Harry M. Fowler\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Film Manufacturing Company]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1921|6}}\n| runtime        = 50 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n\n'''''Desperate Trails''''' is a 1921 American [[Western (genre)|western]] film directed by [[John Ford]] and featuring [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]]. The film is considered to be [[lost film|lost]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DesperateTrails1921.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''Desperate Trails'' |accessdate=March 1, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAs described in a film publication,<ref name=\"FilmDaily\">{{cite journal |title=''Desperate Trails'': Carey Has a Good Story With His Most Recent Universal |journal=Film Daily |volume=16 |issue=86 |page=15 |publisher=Wyd's Films and Film Folks, Inc. |location=New York City |date=June 26, 1921 |url=https://archive.org/details/filmdailyvolume11516newy |accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> Bart Carson (Carey) is in love with Lou (La Marr) and even goes to jail to save Walter A. Walker (Coxen), a man she says is her brother but who is really a husband who has deserted his wife and two children. After he learns the truth, Bart breaks out of jail and trails Walter, who falls off a train trying to escape. Bart then seeks refuge in a cabin with Mrs. Walker (Rich),  where he is captured, but the officials have learned the truth and promise him a pardon.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]] as Bart Carson\n* [[Irene Rich]] as Mrs. Walker\n* George Stone as Dannie Boy\n* Helen Field as Carrie\n* [[Edward Coxen]] as Walter A. Walker\n* [[Barbara La Marr]] as Lady Lou\n* [[George Siegmann]] as Sheriff Price\n* Charles Inslee as Doc Higgins (as Charles E. Insley)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Harry Carey filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Desperate Trails}}\n* {{IMDb title|0012102}}\n\n{{John Ford |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Desperate Trails}}\n[[Category:1921 films]]\n[[Category:1920s Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Ford]]\n[[Category:Lost Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Lost American films]]\n[[Category:1921 lost films]]\n\n{{1920s-silent-Western-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desperate_Trails_(1921_film)"}
